Comment: Queen's Pawn, my favorite opening, as I don't usually like the white side of such openings as the Sicilian and Caro-Kann.
Standard QGD moves so far, the DSB develops to g5 before white plays a solidifying e3 push, so as the dear bishop doesn't end up trapped behind his own pawns.

This move is more unusual, but you can't really say it's inaccurate since it's still development. More typical in the position is 4...Be7 or maybe 4...c6 transposing into a Semi-Slav

This I don't agree with, as trading a bishop for a knight so early is ill-advised in my eyes (unless provoked), seeing as it's much easier to open a position than to close it. These doubled pawns are of no trouble to White either, as c3 further strengthens the all important d4 pawn, and c4 does a good job contesting d5, and can always be traded off if need be. Better than this was 5...O-O, 5...Nbd7 and 5...Nc6
